# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: copper-ale
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 2016, UNESCO inscribed Belgian beer culture on their list of the intangible cultural heritage of humanity.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium, beer was already produced in the Roman era, as evidenced by the excavation of a brewery and malthouse from the 3rd and 4th centuries AD at Ronchinne.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] During the Early and High Middle Ages, beer was produced with gruit, a mix of herbs and spices that was first mentioned in 974 when the bishop of Liège was granted the right to sell it at Fosses-la-Ville.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] From the 14th century onwards, gruit was replaced by hops, after the example of imported beers from northern Germany and Holland.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] After that, several Belgian towns developed their own types of beer for export to other regions, most notably the white beer of Leuven and Hoegaarden, the *caves* of Lier and the *uitzet* of Ghent.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In recent years, the use of gruit has experienced a revival, particularly among homebrewers and eventually by commercial breweries.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] For instance, Gageleer brews a beer using sweet gale (*Myrica gale*) based on a medieval recipe.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Monasteries played only a small role in beer production and mostly brewed for their own consumption and that of their guests.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Monastic brewing would only receive some renown from the late 19th century onwards, when the Trappists of Chimay produced a brown beer that was commercially available.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 1885, a change in legislation made brewing of German-style bottom-fermenting beers viable in Belgium, and it was only from then that large industrial-scale brewing in Belgium took off.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] During the 20th century the number of breweries in Belgium declined from 3223 breweries in 1900 to only 106 breweries in 1993.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Yet, a number of traditional beer styles, such as white beer, lambic and Flemish old brown were preserved, while new local, top-fermented styles developed, such as *spéciale belge*, abbey beer and Belgian strong ale.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 1988, the country's two biggest breweries, Artois and Piedboeuf, formally merged to become Interbrew, then the world's 18th biggest brewer, which was to merge with AmBev in 2004 to become today's AB InBev, the biggest beer producing company in the world.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium, four types of fermentation methods are used for the brewing of beer, which is unique in the world.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a range of colours, brewing methods, and alcohol levels.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Beers brewed in Trappist monasteries are termed Trappist beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] For a beer to qualify for Trappist certification, the brewery must be in a monastery, the monks must play a role in its production and the policies and the profits from the sale must be used to support the monastery or social programs outside.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Only ten monasteries currently meet these qualifications, five of which are in Belgium, two in the Netherlands, one in Austria, one in Italy and one in the United Kingdom.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Trappist beer is a controlled term of origin: it tells where the beers come from, it is not the name of a beer style.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Beyond their being mostly warm fermented, Trappist beers have very little in common stylistically.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the above, a lower-strength beer is sometimes brewed for consumption by the brothers (*patersbier*) or sold on site.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] For example, *l’Orval Vert* (or *Petit Orval*, also known as "Green Orval" or "Small Orval") is served to the monks and guests of the Orval Abbey and can only be consumed on tap in the nearby *À l’Ange Gardien* abbey café.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The designation "abbey beers" (*Bières d'Abbaye* or *Abdijbier*) originally applied to any monastic or monastic-style beer.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] After introduction of an official Trappist beer designation by the International Trappist Association in 1997, it came to mean products similar in style or presentation to monastic beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The requirements for registration under the logo include the monastery having control over certain aspects of the commercial operation, and a proportion of profits going to the abbey or to its designated charities.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Monastic orders other than the Trappists can be and are included in this arrangement.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The "Abbey beer" logo and quality label is no longer used for beers given the name of a fictitious abbey, a vaguely monastic branding or a saint name without mentioning a specific monastery.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some brewers may produce abbey-style beers such as dubbel or tripel, using such names but will refrain from using the term Abbey beer in their branding.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] What connoisseurs now recognize as Trappist breweries began operations in 1838.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Several monasteries, however, maintained "working" breweries for 500+ years before the French regime disrupted religious life (1795–1799).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Even then, some Abbey beers such as Affligem Abbey, whose name now appears on beers made by the Heineken-owned Affligem Brewery, resumed brewing from "working" monasteries until the occupation of most of Belgium in World War I.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Commercial Abbey beers first appeared during Belgium's World War I recovery.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Although Abbey beers do not conform to rigid brewing styles, most tend to include the most recognizable and distinctive Trappist styles of brune (Belgian brown ale, aka dubbel), strong pale ale or tripel, and blonde ale or blond.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Modern abbey breweries range from microbreweries to international giants, but at least one beer writer warns against assuming that closeness of connection with a real monastery confirms a product's quality.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This style makes up the bulk of beer production and consumption in Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgian Pilsners are not particularly distinctive or renowned by connoisseurs.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The top brands include Jupiler (within Belgium) and Stella Artois (both brewed by Inbev), Maes pils and Cristal (both brewed by the Alken Maes branch of Heineken).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Stella Artois, originating in Leuven, Belgium; is distributed globally.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The Pilsnerbeer is which is popularly called "*pintje*" (in Flemish, from English "pint" but in volume only 0.25 cl or roughly 1/2 pint) or "*choppe*" (in French) in Belgium, was the basis of the "*fluitjesbier*" distributed during the German occupation in WWII and under rationing.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This "*fluitjesbier*" was watered down to about 0.8° (compared to fruitjuice which can have up to 1.5° due to natural fermentation).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Bock is a strong lager of German origin.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some Belgian brewers have produced bock-style beers what makes it a style applicable to Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This type of beer, commonly called *witbier* in Dutch, *bière blanche* in French and *wheat beer* in English, originated in the Flemish part of Belgium in the Middle Ages.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Traditionally, it is made with a mixture of wheat and barley.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Before hops became widely available in Europe, beers were flavoured with a mixture of herbs called gruit.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In the later years of the Middle Ages, hops were added to the gruit.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] That mixture continues today in most Belgian white beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The production of this type of beer in Belgium had nearly ended by the late 1950s.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In the town of Hoegaarden, the last *witbier* brewery, Tomsin, closed its doors in 1955.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] However, ten years later, a young farmer by the name of Pierre Celis in the same village decided to try reviving the beer.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 1966, Celis began brewing a "witbier" in his farmhouse.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Ultimately, the Hoegaarden brewery took the name of the village and became successful, gaining international prominence.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] For instance, in 2018, only 8% of the 1.3 million hectoliters of beer produced annually were intended for the Belgian market.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some notable current examples are Celis White, Blanche de Namur and Watou's Wit.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Their alcohol strength is about 5–6 percent ABV, and these beers can be quite refreshing, especially during the warm summer months.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The herb mixture traditionally includes coriander and bitter orange peel, among other herbs.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] White beers also have a moderate light grain sweetness from the wheat used.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In recent times, brewers have been making fruit flavoured wheat beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] These are a light variation on pale ale, often made with pilsner malt.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some beer writers regard blonde and golden ales as distinct styles, while others do not.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Duvel is the archetypal Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Its name means "Devil" and some other blonde beers follow the theme—Satan, Lucifer and Judas for example.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The style is popular with Walloon brewers, the slightly hazy Moinette being the best-known example.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Chouffe can be considered a spiced version (with coriander).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A few Belgian beers are pale and assertively hopped.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] De Ranke's XX Bitter has a British-style name.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Arabier from De Dolle Brouwers.Brouwerij Van Eecke's Poperings Hommelbier, another example, hails from Belgium's hop-growing district.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] From Lambic four kinds of beer are produced: Lambic, Gueuze, Fruit Lambic, and Faro.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] These are beers similar to the traditional pale ales of England, although less bitterly hopped.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A notable example is the 5% ABV De Koninck brand, with its distinctive half-spherical glasses (called 'bollekes').
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] It is popular in its native city of Antwerp.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some, such as Vieux Temps, were based on British styles to please troops stationed in Belgium during World War I.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Others were introduced by the UK-born brewer George Maw Johnson in the late 19th century.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A very strong *ambrée* is brewed by "Bush" (*Dubuisson*), another brewery influenced by British styles.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Walloon amber or *ambrée* ale, such a Gauloise Ambrée, is considered to be somewhat distinct by some beer writers, and to be influenced by the French version of the *ambrée* style.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Tripel is a term used originally by brewers in the Low Countries to describe a strong pale ale, and became associated with *Westmalle Tripel*.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The style of Westmalle's *Tripel* and the name was widely copied by the breweries of Belgium, then the term spread to the US and other countries.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] *Gulden Draak* was awarded the best-tasting beer in the world in 1998 by the *American Tasting Institute* (now ChefsBest).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Dubbel (*double*) has a characteristic brown colour.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] It is one of the classic Abbey/Trappist types, having been developed in the 19th century at the Trappist monastery in Westmalle.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Today, some commercial brewers using abbey names call their strong brown beers "Dubbel".
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Typically, a dubbel is between 6 and 8% abv.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the dubbels made by most Trappist breweries, examples include St.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Bernardus Pater, Adelardus Dubbel, Maredsous 8 and Witkap Dubbel.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Dubbels are characteristically bottle conditioned.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The result is a mildly strong 'drinking' beer with a deep reddish-brown colour and a distinctly acidic, sour yet fruity and mouthy taste.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This style is closely related to Oud bruin.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This style, aged in wooden casks, is a cousin to the sour "Flemish Red" style.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Rodenbach, Goudenband and Petrus.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Regular bruin or brune beers such as Grottenbier are darker than amber ales, less sour than Flemish brown ale, and less strong than dubbel.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] These sweet, heavy-bodied brown ales represent a style which originated in the British Isles.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The Caledonian theme is usually heavily emphasized with tartan and thistles appearing on labels.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Gordon's, Scotch de Silly and La Chouffe Mc Chouffe.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgian stouts subdivide into sweeter and drier, and stronger and weaker versions.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Callewaerts and Ellezelloise Hercule.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The sweeter versions resemble the almost-defunct British style "milk stout", while the stronger ones are sometimes described as Imperial stouts.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Champagne style beers are generally ales that are finished "à la méthode originale" for champagne.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Examples include Grottenbier, DeuS and Malheur Bière Brut.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] They receive a second fermentation much like Champagne does and are stored for several months "sûr lie" while the fermentation lasts.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] This creates the smaller, softer bubbles that we know from Champagne, but maintains the beer flavour and style.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In Belgium "Grand Cru" is more often used than "Quadrupel", these beers are a mostly a blend of brews, which is often refermented as a blend.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Saison (French for "season") is the name originally given to refreshing, low-alcohol beers brewed seasonally in Wallonia, the French-speaking region of Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] First seen in early 19th century Liège, saisons gained notoriety as a luxury beer in 20th century Hainaut brewed by city and countryside brewers alike.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] By the 1980s, they were only produced on the countryside.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Modern-day saisons are also brewed in other countries, particularly USA, and are generally bottle conditioned, with an average range of 5 to 8% ABV, though saisons at the more traditional 3.5% strength can still be found.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Although saison has been described as an endangered style, there has been a rise in interest in this style in recent years, with Saison Dupont being named "the Best Beer in the World" by the magazine *Men's Journal* in July 2005.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A related style known as a grisette was brewed with a lower ABV and with wheat added.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Many breweries produce special beers during December.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Most contain more alcohol than the brewery's other types of beer and may also contain spicing.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] An annual beer festival in Essen near Antwerp focuses on this type of beer with over 190 beers available for tasting in 2014.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some brewers that are not Lambic-brewers make fruit beers in a similar process as the Fruit Lambic beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] All brewers of this style make fruit lambic.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Many brewers of top fermentation beers such as Belgian golden ales, ambers and Flemish old brown beers, that produce beers that usually go through a multiple stage fermentation process, are catching on to the trend to make fruit beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The process starts after the first fermentation of the wort, when sometimes sugar is added to referment the beer on wooden casks.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] To make fruit beer the fruit, juice or syrup is added (instead of sugar) to the first brew and refermented, these may be termed fruit lambics or fruit beers, depending on the type of first brew.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Beer that has fruit syrup or fruit lemonade added after (the final stage of) fermentation, in other words as a flavouring, are termed "Radlers" ("Shandy" in the UK) definitely not fruit beer.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Beers above 7%, such as tripels or strong dubbels, are referred to in some sources as Belgian strong ale, although this is not a name used by Belgian brewers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a wide range of styles and brewing methods and are almost always served in unique, branded glassware.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Each glass is designed to enhance the beer’s taste and aroma, often featuring the brewery’s logo or a beer-specific design.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgian "heavy" or "special" beers (stronger or bottled beers) are usually served in more elaborate branded beer glassware.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some glasses are etched on the bottom; typically with the brewery’s logo, to nucleate a stream of bubbles for maintaining a nice head.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Unless the bar is out of the specific glass that goes with that beer it is usually served in its own glass.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Most bartenders or waitresses will apologize if the beer comes in a different glass.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Pils (pilsner) or pale lager, remains the most widely produced and consumed beer style in Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] One of the most typical Belgian pilsner glasses is the ribbed glass, often referred to as the *ribbelke* or *ribbelglas*.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The Belgian pilsner glass originated between 1860 and 1900.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Its ribbed base was designed to minimize heat transfer from the drinker’s hand, preventing the beer from warming.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Additionally, the glass’s tall, narrow, and straight shape is suited to pilsner beers due to their lower foaming protein content, necessitating a smaller diameter to maintain an appropriate head.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A regional variation is the *Boerke* glass, which translates to "small farmer".
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The question of which glass is best suited for Belgian pilsner remains a subject of debate, influenced by factors such as personal preference, brand loyalty, tradition, regional customs, and differing opinions among Belgians.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] One of the more common types is the tulip glass.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A tulip glass not only helps trap the aroma, but also aids in maintaining large heads, creating a visual and olfactory sensation.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The body is bulbous, but the top flares out to form a lip which helps foam head retention.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A vessel similar to a champagne flute is the preferred serving vessel for Belgian (fruit) Lambics, Gueuze and fruit beers.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The narrow shape helps maintain carbonation, while providing a strong aromatic front.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Flute glasses display the lively carbonation, sparkling colour, and soft lacing of this distinct style.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Traditionally, lambic beers including gueuze and fruit lambics are served in a tall glass resembling the ribbed pilsner glass.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] However, the edges and base of the lambic glass are significantly thicker; which originated from the old custom of grinding sugar at the bottom of the glass before serving, allowing drinkers to sweeten the beer to their taste, as lambic styles are known for their intense sourness.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The glass is commonly referred to as a *lambiekstoemper* (or "lambic stomper"), a name that reflects the practice of crushing sugar with a tool similar to a cocktail muddler.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Chalices and goblets are large, stemmed, bowl-shaped glasses mainly associated with Trappist and Abbey ales.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The distinction between goblet and chalice is typically in the glass thickness.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Goblets tend to be more delicate and thin, while the chalice is heavy and thick walled.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] However, a more recent addition, though not traditionally Belgian, is the TeKu beer glass, developed in 2006 by Teo Musso and Kuaska (hence the acronym).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Designed as a universal beer glass, it has since been embraced by the craft beer community, particularly for styles such as pale ales, IPAs, stouts...
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In addition to the profusion of glasses provided by brewers, some Belgian beer cafés serve beer in their own "house" glassware.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The majority of Belgian beer brands are sold in reusable bottles.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Draught beers tend mostly to be pale lagers, wheat beers, regional favourites such as kriek in Brussels or De Koninck in Antwerp; and the occasional one-off.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] These days, Belgian beers are sold in brown- (or sometimes dark green-) tinted glass bottles (to avoid negative effects of light on the beverage) and sealed with a cork, a metal crown cap, or sometimes both.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some beers are bottle conditioned, meaning reseeded with yeast so that an additional fermentation may take place.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Different bottle sizes exist: 25 cl, 33 cl, 37.5 cl, 75 cl and multiples of 75.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] (8, 12, 24 or multiples of 24 fl. oz.) The 37.5 cl size is usually for lambics.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Other beers are generally bottled in 25 or 33 cl format (depending on brands).
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The bigger bottles (75 cl) are sold almost in every food shop but customers do not always have an extensive choice.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Bottles larger than 75 cl are named following the terminology used for champagne and are limited in quantity.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In Brussels or Walloon Belgian cafés, you can order orders a *demi* (English: "half"), which is a 50 cl draught beer.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The prominence of the Belgian beer culture is reflected in the extensive range of beers offered in nearly every café across the country.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Belgium contains thousands of cafés that offer a wide selection of beers, a typical beer menu ranges from at least half a dozen draught beers and two dozen bottled beers of different types in a neighborhood café, to over 1000 in a specialist beer café.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Although many major brands of beer are available at most supermarkets, off-licences located throughout the country generally offer a far wider selection, albeit at somewhat higher prices.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 2024, Belgium exported around 70% of its beer production, amounting to approximately 14 million hectoliters.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some draught-beer brands produced by AB InBev like Stella Artois, Hoegaarden and Leffe are available in several European countries.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Aside from these, mostly bottled beer is exported across Europe.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Cafés, exclusively or primarily offering Belgian beers, exist beyond Belgium in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, France, the United Kingdom and the United States, amongst others.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Some beer festivals outside Belgium have a Belgian beer bar as an alternative to local products.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In North America, a growing number of draught Belgian beer brands have started to become available, often at "Belgian Bars".
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Such brands include Brasserie Brunehaut, Karmeliet, Kwak, Maredsous, Mont Saint-Aubert, Delirium, Palm, Rodenbach and St.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] A number of traditional Belgian dishes use beer as an ingredient.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] One is *carbonade* (French) or *stoverij* or *stoofvlees* (Dutch), a stew of beef cooked in beer, similar to Boeuf bourguignon.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The beer used is typically the regional speciality—lambic in Brussels, De Koninck in Antwerp, and so on—so that the taste of the dish varies.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] *In't Spinnekopke*, Brussels, and *Den Dyver*, Bruges are famed for their beer cookery.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] In 1998 Anheuser-Busch InBev started a worldwide chain of bars/restaurants, Belgian Beer Cafe, serving typical Belgian dishes combined with Belgian Beer.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Beer writers who have written extensively on Belgian beer include Belgians Peter Crombeq, Gert van Lierde and Erik Verdonck, and Britons Michael Jackson and Tim Webb.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] The following list contains beers that are brewed in Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/abbey-beers] Not to be confused with "Belgian style" beers that are produced in other countries, and may or may not resemble a style that is specific to Belgium.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] In brewing, **adjuncts** are unmalted grains (such as barley, wheat, maize, rice, rye, and oats) or grain products used in brewing beer which supplement the main mash ingredient (such as malted barley).
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] This is often done with the intention of cutting costs, but sometimes also to create an additional feature, such as better foam retention, flavours or nutritional value or additives.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Both solid and liquid adjuncts are commonly used.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Ingredients which are standard for certain beers, such as wheat in a wheat beer, may be termed adjuncts when used in beers which could be made without them — such as adding wheat to a pale ale for the purpose of creating a lasting head.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] The sense here is that the ingredient is additional and strictly unnecessary, though it may be beneficial and attractive.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Under the Bavarian *Reinheitsgebot* purity law it would be considered that an adjunct is *any* beer ingredient other than water, barley, hops, and yeast; this, however, is an antiquated view.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] This purity law originated in 16th-century Germany and did not initially include yeast due to the fact that it had not been discovered yet.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] The term adjunct is often used to refer to corn, rice, oats, unmalted barley and rye.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] The use of ingredients as substitutes for the main starch source is where the term adjunct is most often used.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Adjuncts can be broadly classified according to the physical form in which they are used into solids and liquid syrups.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Barley is used as an un-malted grain at up to 10% of the grist.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Barley provides both carbohydrates and proteins to the wort; on the negative side, the cell walls of the un-malted barley contain high levels of beta-glucans that affect wort viscosity and create haze problems in the bright beer.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Barley is also used in the mash as roasted barley to provide colour to the beer.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Cassava is a novel adjunct used in Africa either as a wet cake or as a purified starch.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Corn is commonly used in the production of American-style pale lagers, particularly malt liquor.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Corn is generally used in brewing as corn syrup, and as such is highly fermentable.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Corn is cheaper than barley, so it is used as a cost-saving measure.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Oatmeal stouts usually do not specifically taste of oats.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] The smoothness of oatmeal stouts comes from the high content of proteins, lipids, and gums imparted by the use of oats.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] The gums increase the viscosity and body adding to the sense of smoothness.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Rice is sometimes used in the production of pale lagers, most notably Anheuser-Busch's Budweiser.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Anheuser-Busch is the largest North American buyer of U.S. rice.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Rice may be used to lighten the body and the mouthfeel, or increase alcohol content, or add a little sweetness.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Rye is used in *roggenbiers* from Germany and in rye beers from America.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Rye is notoriously difficult to brew with, so most rye beers only include a small amount of rye.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Rye provides a spicy flavour to beer and dramatically increases head formation.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sorghum is used in Africa as a local ingredient saving on expensive imported malt and developing the local agricultural sector.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sorghum has a high gelatinisation temperature and is added to a mash cooker to gelatinise the starch before adding to the mash tun.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sorghum has been used for hundreds of years as the main ingredient in many of the indigenous traditional African beers.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sorghum can be used in the malted or the un-malted form.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Wheat is used in German and American wheat beers, in lambic and other Belgian ales, and in English ales.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Wheat lightens the body, improves head retention, and provides a tart flavour.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Wheat beers are often served with fruit syrups or slices of lemon in the US and Germany.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] In England, beans were occasionally used as an ingredient in beer brewing.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sugar adjuncts provide only carbohydrates and if used at high levels will result in wort lacking in amino acids and this may lead to poor yeast growth causing tailing fermentations and poor yeast crops.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Primings sugars such as maple syrup, honey, and molasses are common in craft beers and homebrew.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Candi sugar is a common ingredient in strong Belgian ales, where it increases the beer's strength while keeping the body fairly light; dark varieties of candi sugar also affect the colour and flavour of the beer.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Caramel syrup is used to provide colour to brews and can either be added in the wort kettle or at filtration when needed to correct low beer colours.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] This caramel is not sweet and provides little or no fermentable extract.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Honey is a primary fermentable in mead, and can be used for flavour (though also supplying some fermentable sugar) in beer.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Sucrose may come from sugar-cane or from sugar-beet.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] A number of traditional beer styles are brewed with spices.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] For example, Belgian *witbier* and German *gose* are brewed with coriander, Finnish *sahti* is brewed with juniper berries, and traditional beers in Britain are brewed with honey and spices.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Also, some strong winter beers are flavoured with nutmeg or cinnamon, while ginger is a popular flavouring for a range of beers.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Many commercially available pumpkin ales are made with pumpkin pie spices without any actual pumpkin.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Spices may be added to the wort during the boil or spices or spice extract may be added at any time during fermentation depending on desired results.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Other, less common flavourings include chocolate, coffee, milk, chili peppers and even oysters.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Beer may be brewed with a fruit or vegetable adjunct or flavouring.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Fruits have been used as a beer adjunct or flavouring for centuries, especially with Belgian lambic styles.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Cherry, raspberry, and peach are a common addition to this style of beer.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Modern breweries may add only flavoured extracts to the finished product, rather than actually fermenting the fruit.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Pumpkin-flavoured beers are brewed seasonally in the autumn in North America.
[src:copper-ale/adjuncts] Chile pepper is used to flavour pale lagers.
[src:copper-ale/ale] As with most beers, ale typically has a bittering agent to balance the malt and act as a preservative.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Ale was originally bittered with gruit, a mixture of herbs or spices boiled in the wort before fermentation, before hops replaced gruit as the bittering agent.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In England, however, it was also common to brew ale without adding herbs.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The word *ale* comes into English from its ancestor-language, Proto-Germanic.
[src:copper-ale/ale] English belongs to the West Germanic branch of Proto-Germanic, and some other languages in this branch also attest to the word: Middle Dutch *āle* and *ael*, and the Old Saxon word *alo-fat* 'ale-cup'.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The word is also found throughout the North Germanic languages, almost certainly appearing in ancient runic inscriptions in the form *alu*, and subsequently in Old Norse as *ǫl*.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Through linguistic reconstruction it is possible to infer that the Common Germanic form of this word was **alúþ-*.
[src:copper-ale/ale] According to the third edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, however, the origin of this word is 'uncertain and disputed'.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Research by Harald Bjorvand, however, has favoured the following explanation: the Germanic word **alú-þ-* descends from the Indo-European word ***olú-t-* (from an earlier Indo-European base **h₂elut-*), which originally meant 'golden or reddish colour'.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Other Indo-European words related to this root include Old Indic *aruṣá-* ('reddish'; the *r* comes from an earlier *l*, **alu-sá-*) and Old High German *elo* ('yellowy, pale yellow, reddish yellow, tawny').
[src:copper-ale/ale] The Indo-European word **olú-t-* then came to refer specifically to ale because this is its colour, giving rise to both the Germanic word **alú-þ-* and the Ossetic word *æluton*.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In this account, the Indo-European word **olú-t-* was also borrowed into the Finnic languages, giving Finnish *olut* and Estonian *õlu*.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The relationship of similar words in the Slavonic languages (such as Old Bulgarian *olu* 'cider', Slovenian *ol* 'beer') and the Baltic languages (Lithuanian *alus*, Latvian *alus*, 'beer', Old Prussian *alu* 'mead') remains uncertain.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Ale was an important source of nutrition in the medieval world.
[src:copper-ale/ale] It was one of three main sources of grain in the diet at the start of the fourteenth century in England, along with pottage and bread.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Scholars believe grains accounted for around 80% of the calorie intake of agricultural workers and 75% for soldiers - even nobles received around 65% of their calories from grains.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Small beer, also known as table beer or mild beer, which was highly nutritious, contained just enough alcohol to act as a preservative, and provided hydration without intoxicating effects.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Small beer would have been consumed daily by almost everyone, including children, in the medieval world, with higher-alcohol ales served for recreational purposes.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The lower cost for proprietors combined with the lower taxes levied on small beer inevitably led to the selling of some beer labeled "strong beer" that had actually been diluted with small beer.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Records from the Middle Ages show that ale was consumed in huge quantities.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In 1272, a husband and wife who retired at Selby Abbey were given 2 gallons of ale per day with two loaves of white bread and one loaf of brown bread.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Monks at Westminster Abbey consumed 1 gallon of ale each day.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In 1299, Henry de Lacy's household purchased an average of 85 gallons of ale daily and in 1385–86 Framlingham Castle consumed 78 gallons per day.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Brewing ale in the Middle Ages was a local industry primarily pursued by women.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Brewsters, or alewives, would brew in the home for both domestic consumption and small scale commercial sale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Brewsters provided a substantial supplemental income for families; however, only in select few cases, as was the case for widows, was brewing considered the primary income of the household.
[src:copper-ale/ale] From the mid-17th century, strong ales became particularly fashionable.
[src:copper-ale/ale] They were known by names such as Huff-Cap, Nippitate and Hum-Cup, so called because it caused "a humming sensation in the head".
[src:copper-ale/ale] Strong ale, like wine, was typically decanted due to the high sediment content into small glasses, which were better suited to the high ABV ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Modern ale is typically fermented at temperatures between 15 and 24 °C (59 and 75 °F).
[src:copper-ale/ale] At temperatures above 24 °C (75 °F) the yeast can produce significant amounts of esters and other secondary flavour and aroma products, and the result is often a beer with slightly "fruity" compounds resembling those found in fruits, such as apple, pear, pineapple, banana, plum, cherry, or prune.
[src:copper-ale/ale] When ale ferments, it naturally creates two prevalent byproducts, those being Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) and Hydrogen Sulfide (H2S).
[src:copper-ale/ale] Each of these compounds affects the product in different ways, and each can be managed before and during the fermenting process to create different flavours and benefits for the ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Sulfur Dioxide is a product of some of the initial ingredients of ale and is produced during the fermentation of the wort.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Sulfur Dioxide helps to increase an ale's shelf life; however, it naturally occurs in foods when they become old, so many people react negatively to its smell and can even be viewed as an allergen in some countries.
[src:copper-ale/ale] During the stages of fermentation of ale, the production of SO2 works as an antioxidant, a preservative, and, in addition, it works to fight bacteria.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Throughout the fermentation process, one of the ways in which brewers can control the levels of SO2 is through temperature during brewing, and another way to preserve that reaction is by tempering with the temperature at which the product is stored.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The cooler it is stored, the more SO2 is preserved, which helps the ale keep its flavour.
[src:copper-ale/ale] When an ale becomes stale from oxidation, it loses its natural flavours; it could taste like any multitude of different undesirable things, depending on the initial flavour of the ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Some of the most common tastes for people are that of sherry, where the flavours have gotten negatively sweeter, or that of cardboard or paper, where it tastes stale and bland.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Hydrogen sulfide is another byproduct of fermentation.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In yeast strains, it helps the yeast grow and also works as an antioxidant later in the fermentation process.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Having a chemical compound including sulfur, however, means that it has a pungent smell that people often associate with rotten eggs, which can later affect the produced ale negatively, so producing and managing a finite amount of hydrogen sulfide is very important in the fermenting of ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] When controlled, the amount of H2S is generally unnoticeable and does not affect the overall smell or taste, but still does its job of keeping the shelf life of the ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] While making ale, sugar can be added either during the boiling stage or the fermenting stage; however, both times lead to similar outcomes, just at different levels of effectiveness.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The benefits of adding sugar to a brew can be to increase the overall APV levels of the brew and the flavour at the end of the brewing process.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Due to the higher APV, however, the body of the beer can often be left thinner, having a water-like consistency.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Both the factors of APV levels and flavour depend on what type of sugar you are adding, and oftentimes, when you add them in the process.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Generally, the later a sugar is added to the brew, the more prominent the flavour will be.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Sugar can be added so long as it is fermentable, which most common sugars are.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Generally, brewers will add different syrups, saps, honeys, and syrups to their ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Flocculation is the tendency for the yeast to conglomerate into large masses at the top and bottom of the fermentation tank at the end of the fermentation process.
[src:copper-ale/ale] This selective trait in the yeast came about as the majority of the yeast that gets repurposed is that which aggregates and gets easily removed.
[src:copper-ale/ale] This selective trait is gradually characterized in most yeast as the yeast that exhibits this behavior lasts a greater number of generations.
[src:copper-ale/ale] "Real ale" is a British term, coined by the Campaign for Real Ale, for cask and bottle-conditioned beer.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The following list breaks the many various ales into separate, diverse categories.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ales listed are categorized into their respective style groups of origin and accompanied by information regarding the specific brew.
[src:copper-ale/ale] For further classification, more comprehensive information can be found in the Brewers Association Style Guide.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In 18th-century England, brewers coined the term "pale ale" to distinguish this golden-hued ale from the more prevalent dark ales of the time.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The use of hops during fermentation introduces a distinctive bitter aroma, while the general absence of diacetyl groups and the presence of esters contribute to a sweeter and fruitier flavour compared to other ales.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The average alcohol by volume (ABV) of these ales ranges from 3.2% to 5.3%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Scotch ale, also known as "wee heavy", boasts an exceptionally malty taste accented by sweet malty undertones due to the heavy concentration of esters.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Generally low in bitterness, it exhibits a deep caramel colour, the shade of which may vary depending on the brewing techniques.
[src:copper-ale/ale] They have a relatively high ABV, falling between 6.6% and 8.5%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] British-style summer ale is characteristically lighter in gold colour.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Filled with esters, this beer yields a fruity flavour and maintains a subdued yet weak profile in bitterness and hop.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale is traditionally high in carbonation due to its respective brewing techniques.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Falling within the standard ABV range of 3.7% to 5.1% aligns with most beer's typical potency.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Old ale is classified as an intensely dark red ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] It is said to have a fruity aroma, with brewers occasionally adding caramel to sweeten the product.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The hop flavouring and bitterness of an old ale are relatively low compared to other types of categorized ales.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Adequately brewing an old ale involves an aging process spanning a few years.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Upon completion, it yields an extremely sweet drink comparable to wine.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The final ABV of the ale ranges from 5.0% to 9.3%, with higher percentages correlating to the amount of sugar added during fermentation.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Brown ale, distinguished by its dark hue, is commonly enriched with a blend of roasted and caramel malts, leading to a distinctively unique toffee-flavoured ale.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Both esters and diacetyl are found in low levels, contributing to the beer's unique taste.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ABV of brown ales typically ranges between 4.2% and 6.0%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Barley wine is known for its balance of flavour and high alcohol content.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale's colour varies widely depending on the duration of its age, as its flavour profile evolves dramatically over time.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Low levels of diacetyl and carbonation are found in all barely wines, while esters are found in high quantities, contributing to a low bitter fruity flavour and aroma.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The flavours of barley wines are diverse, ranging from bread-like to hints of molasses and toffee.
[src:copper-ale/ale] They have an unusually high ABV, ranging from 8.5% to 12.2%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] India pale ale, commonly shortened to IPA, is a hoppy pale ale which was originally shipped to colonial India.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Its high hop content prevented spoilage during the long sea course from England to India.
[src:copper-ale/ale] IPA is full bodied and hoppy, it is amber coloured and usually somewhat opaque.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ABV of IPA can fall within the range of 4.5–20%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Amber ale is an American craft beer named after the hue it possesses from being flavoured using caramel malt.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale is brewed with an assortment of hops and has a balanced flavour.
[src:copper-ale/ale] It maintains a low level of esters and lacks any trace of diacetyl, leading to a moderately bitter and slightly fruity undertone.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ABV of amber ales ranges anywhere from 4.4% to 5.4%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Sour ale, more commonly known as wild ale, is characterized by a unique sour flavour, produced during fermentation when acid-producing bacteria like lactobacillus or acetobacter feed on sugars.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The acidity produced comes from mild concentrations of lactic or acetic acid and further develops during the aging process.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Utilizing wooden bourbon barrels imbued with either vanillin or sherry plays a crucial role in augmenting the beer's flavour complexity during aging.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The presence of esters and diacetyl fluctuates depending on the sought-after flavour profile of the brew.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The final ABV varies widely depending on the length and methods used during brewing.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Table beer typically has a low ABV of around 0.5% - 2.0%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Popular in Eastern Europe, these beverages are brewed with malt barley, wheat, oats, or rye.
[src:copper-ale/ale] They are commonly flavoured with additive sugar and either orange or lemon peels to yield a citrus-like flavouring.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Session ale, named for its purpose of being enjoyed within a single "session" without inducing significant intoxication, features a low ABV, typically ranging from 3% to 5%.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Though they share similarities with table beers, they maintain a higher alcohol percentage.
[src:copper-ale/ale] They are characterized by a balanced flavour profile, as the production method does not stray far from traditional ale brewing.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Esters may be present in medium quantities adding sweetness to the final flavour, while diacetyl is non-existent.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Most commercially available ales fall under the distinction of session ales due to their cost-effective ability to be brewed in mass.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The flavour profile of dark ale is characterized by a malty sweetness resulting from the abundance of esters in the brew.
[src:copper-ale/ale] A discernible spiciness is attributed to yeast-derived phenolic compounds present in moderate quantities.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Depending on the brand, the beer tends to have a modest level of bitterness owing to the hops during fermentation.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The aroma of the brew is described as subtle yet persistent, due to phenol compounds.
[src:copper-ale/ale] In terms of ABV, dark ale ranks notably high compared to other brews, ranging from 7.1% to 11.2%, often veiled by its diverse flavour profile.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Bière de Garde is a hybrid beer whose name translates from French to English as “Beer for Keeping”.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale is low to moderate in esters and contains a similar malt sweetness to most other ales.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale's ABV ranges from 4.4% to 8% and has a range of appearances, with its primary descriptions being “Light Amber, Chestnut Brown, or Red.” While most popular in France, this style has become much more frequent in the U.S. as the ale industry grows.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Irish red ale is characterized by its definitive amber or dark red hue, having an ABV ranging from 4.0% to 4.8%, and having a standard approachable bitterness, all of which make this ale highly sessionable.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Medium flavours of candy-like caramel malt distinguish the ale, and a tan foam forms at the top, due to the inclusion of roasted barley.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Originating in the Düsseldorf region of Germany, Altbier pays homage to traditional brewing methods, with "alt" meaning old in English.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The complexion ranges from light amber to a deep copper colour.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Esters are present in low quantities, which is attributed to their lightly citrus profile, while diacetyls are completely absent.
[src:copper-ale/ale] The ale boasts a moderate level of bitterness owing to hops utilized in fermentation.
[src:copper-ale/ale] Its ultimate ABV falls within the range of 4.6% to 5.6%, aligning typically with other ales.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Altbier is usually a dark, copper colour.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] It is fermented at a moderate temperature using a top-fermenting yeast—which gives its flavour some fruitiness.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Because Altbier is then matured at a cooler temperature, its flavour is more akin to lager beer styles than is the norm for top-fermented beers (such as British pale ale).
[src:copper-ale/altbier] It generally has an ABV between 4.3% and 5.5%.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] The first producer to use the name Altbier—to contrast its top-fermenting beer with the bottom-fermenting kinds—was the Schumacher brewery of Düsseldorf, that opened in 1838.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Mass-market brewers of Altbier include Diebels and the Radeberger Gruppe under the brands Schlösser Alt and Hansa Alt.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] These are complemented by small breweries in Düsseldorf and other nearby cities.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Some Altbier breweries have a tradition of producing a stronger version, called *sticke alt*, coming from a local dialect word meaning "secret".
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Originally made as a special reserve beer intended for the brewers' own consumption, today it is generally a seasonal or special occasion brew.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] There exists a regional rivalry between the drinkers of Altbier in the Düsseldorf area and the drinkers of Kölsch beer in the Cologne (Köln) area.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] A beer variety associated with the Lower Rhine region, Altbier is especially found in Düsseldorf, Krefeld, and Mönchengladbach.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Füchschen, Uerige, Schlüssel and Kürzer are all brewed and sold in the Altstadt (Old Town).
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Schumacher is between the Altstadt and the main train station (Hauptbahnhof), although it also has a pub in the Altstadt, Im Goldenen Kessel, across the street from Schlüssel.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Each brewpub produces a seasonal "Sticke" variant in small quantities, though the names vary: Schlüssel spells it "Stike", without the "c", while Schumacher calls its special beer "Latzenbier", meaning "slat beer", possibly because the kegs from which it was poured had been stored on raised shelves.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Füchschen's seasonal is its Weihnachtsbier (Christmas beer), available in bottles starting mid-November, and served in the brewpub on Christmas Eve.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Altbier is somewhat similar to Cologne's native beer style *Kölsch*, being warm-fermented at a lower temperature than British ales, and Altbier proper is also brewed as "Ehrenfelder Alt", in Cologne's smallest brewery "Braustelle".
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Pinkus Müller brewery in Münster produces an Altbier which is quite different to the Düsseldorf style, being pale and slightly tart.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Altbier has been produced in the city of Venlo in the Netherlands since at least 1753.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Venlo is on the border to Germany approximately 50 km (30 miles) from Düsseldorf.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] The beer was produced up until the Second World War, but then had a hiatus until its revival in 1983.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] It is produced by the Lindeboom brewery, who bought the recipe in 2001.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Altbier is brewed in small quantities in Austria, Switzerland, Hungary, Liechtenstein, the UK, the United States, Canada, Australia by Tooheys in Sydney New South Wales, New Zealand, Japan, South Africa, Norway, Brazil and Australia.
[src:copper-ale/altbier] Versions of altbier are brewed in the United States, though not always to traditional recipes, with Widmer Brothers often considered the first American brewer to produce the style.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Coke had been first used for dry roasting malt in 1642, but it was not until around 1703 that the term *pale ale* was first applied to beers made from such malt.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] By 1784, advertisements appeared in the *Calcutta Gazette* for "light and excellent" pale ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] By 1830, the expressions *bitter* and *pale ale* were synonymous.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Breweries tended to designate beers as "pale ales", though customers would commonly refer to the same beers as "bitters".
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] It is thought that customers used the term *bitter* to differentiate these pale ales from other less noticeably hopped beers such as porters and milds.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Different brewing practices and hop levels have resulted in a range of taste and strength within the pale ale family.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Collier Brothers of London applied for the UK trademark of *The Amber Ale* in 1876 and the trademark was maintained through changes in ownership until it expired in 2002.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] It was a "pure delicately hopped Pale Ale" positioned between their light bitter and IPA.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Since the expiry of the trademark some traditional British bitters have been rebranded as amber ales, in some cases to distinguish them from golden ales sold under the same brand.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Anchor Liberty Ale, a 6% abv ale originally brewed by the Anchor Brewing Company as a special in 1975 to commemorate Paul Revere's "Midnight Ride" in 1775, was seen by Michael Jackson, a writer on beverages, as the first modern American ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The brewery thought to be the first to successfully use significant quantities of American hops in the notably hoppy style of an APA and use the specific name "pale ale" was the Sierra Nevada Brewing Company.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] It brewed the first experimental batch of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale in November 1980, distributing the finished version in March 1981.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Other pioneers of a hoppy American pale ale are Jack McAuliffe of the New Albion Brewing Company and Bert Grant of Yakima Brewing.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] American pale ales are generally around 5% abv, with significant quantities of American hops, typically Cascade.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Although American-brewed beers tend to use a cleaner yeast, and American two row malt, it is the use of strong American hops in particular that distinguish an APA from a British or European pale ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The style is close to the American India pale ale (IPA), and boundaries blur, though IPAs are stronger and more assertively hopped.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The style is also close to amber ale, though these are darker and maltier due to the use of crystal malts.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The origin of the name lies in the tradition that it was matured or cellared for a period of time once bottled (most were sealed with a cork), to be consumed later in the year, akin to a saison.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Among the better French known "*bières de garde*" are Brasserie de Saint-Sylvestre, Trois Monts, Brasseurs Duyck, Jenlain and Brasserie La Choulette, *ambrée*.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The term "blonde" for pale beers is common in Europe and South America – particularly in France, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, the UK, and Brazil – though the beers may not have much in common, other than colour.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Blondes tend to be clear, crisp, and dry, with low-to-medium bitterness and aroma from hops, and some sweetness from malt.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Fruitiness from esters may be perceived.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] A lighter body from higher carbonation may be noticed.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] In the United Kingdom, golden or summer ales were developed in the late 20th century by breweries to compete with the pale lager market.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] A typical golden ale has an appearance and profile similar to that of a pale lager.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Malt character is subdued and the hop profile ranges from spicy to citrus; common hops include Styrian Golding and Cascade.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The UK style is attributed to John Gilbert, owner of Hop Back Brewery, who developed "Summer Lightning" in 1989, which won several awards and inspired numerous imitators.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Belgian blondes are often made with pilsner malt.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Duvel is a typical Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Burton retained absolute dominance in pale ale brewing until a chemist, C.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Vincent, discovered the process of Burtonization to reproduce the chemical composition of the water from Burton-upon-Trent, thus giving any brewery the capability to brew pale ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The expression *English bitter* first appeared in the early 19th century as part of the development and spread of pale ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] India pale ale (IPA) is a style of pale ale developed in England for export to India.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The first known use of the expression "India pale ale" is in an advertisement in the *Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser* on 27 August 1829.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Worthington White Shield, originating in Burton-upon-Trent, is a beer considered to be part of the development of India pale ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The colour of an IPA can vary from a light gold to a reddish amber.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The term "Irish red ale" was popularised in the United States and subsequently exported worldwide.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] The additional variants "red ale", "Irish ale" (Irish: *leann dearg*,) and "Irish red", have come to be used by brewers mainly in Ireland and the United States, less so elsewhere.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Smithwick's and Kilkenny are typical examples of macro-brewed commercial Irish red ale.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] There are many other smaller and craft examples, such as O'Hara's, Sullivan's, Murphy's, Porterhouse and Franciscan Well.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Irish red ales are characterised by their malt profile and typically have a sweet, caramel or toffee-like taste, low bitterness and amber to red colour - hence the name.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Irish brewers have increasingly adopted the term Irish Red Ale to distinguish their beers in both the domestic and international markets.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] In the US, the name can also be used simply to describe a darker amber ale, or the abbreviated term "Irish Red" applied to a "reddish" beer brewed as a lager and ambered with caramel colouring - for example Killian's Irish Red.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] Strong pale ales are ales made predominantly with pale malts and have an alcohol strength that may start around 5%, though typically at 7 or 8% by volume, and may go up to 12%, though some brewers have been pushing the alcohol strength higher to produce novelty beers.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] In 1994, the Hair of the Dog Brewing Company produced a strong pale ale with an alcohol by volume of 29%.
[src:copper-ale/amber-ale] In 2010, Brewdog released "Sink the Bismarck!", a 41% abv pale ale, which is stronger than typical U.S. distilled spirits (40% abv).
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] The **American lager** or **North American lager** is a style of pale lager produced in the United States and Canada.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Pale lagers originated in Europe in the mid-19th century and were brought to North America by German immigrants.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] While the Bavarian and Czech variants of this style may be firmly hopped, pale lager has developed into a modestly hopped beer in the rest of the world and sometimes uses adjuncts such as rice or corn – this is also true in the US and Canada.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] The best-known American lagers worldwide are Anheuser-Busch InBev's Budweiser and Bud Light, although several other prominent brands are produced by MillerCoors; these include Coors Light, Coors Banquet, Miller Lite, and Miller High Life.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Pale lager is the predominant choice among the largest brewing companies of United States of America, although it is not common in U.S. microbreweries.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Likewise, in Canada the biggest-selling commercial beers, including both domestics such as Molson Canadian, Labatt Blue, Kokanee, Carling Black Label, and Old Style Pilsner, and imports such as Budweiser and Coors are very lightly hopped pale lagers.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] This is by far the largest-selling style in Canada.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Just as in the United States, Canadian microbrewers typically do not produce North American-style pale lagers.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] The United States and Canada were traditionally ale (and whisky) consuming regions in the British traditions before the late 19th century.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Pale lager was later introduced by German immigrants.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] These German brewers developed their beers from the American six-row barley which has a higher tannic acid and protein content and greater husk per weight than the two-row barley typical in continental Europe.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] In addition, the Tettnanger and Saaz hops of Europe were not available.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Therefore, to balance taste, and dilute the excessive protein, the grain mixture was adjusted by adding up to 30% corn to the barley malt mash.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] However, the beer was brewed to full European strength and to the practices of a pale lager style.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Later, rice gained popularity in the domestic brewing market during World War II, due to grain rationing on the home-front.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Most breweries were unable to afford the necessary amounts of barley required for production and so began using rice as a filler.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] After the war, the process was not changed.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] These corporate brewers reacted to a new taste for sweet drinks in a public that had switched to sugary soft drinks and "near-beer" during prohibition.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Large-scale representatives of the pre-Prohibition lager style in the United States are D.G.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] Yuengling & Son with its traditional lager; Genesee Brewing Company with its Genesee beer; and August Schell Brewing Company with its Original.
[src:copper-ale/american-lager] A number of smaller American breweries have also reintroduced it, such as Victory Brewing Company with its Headwaters Pale Ale, North Coast Brewing Company with Scrimshaw Pilsner, and Full Sail Brewing Company with its Session Lager.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] American pale ales are generally around 5% abv with significant quantities of American hops, typically Cascade.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] Although American brewed beers tend to use a cleaner yeast, and American two row malt, it is particularly the American hops that distinguish an APA from British or European pale ales.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] The style is also close to amber ale, though ambers are darker and maltier due to use of crystal malts.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] Anchor Liberty Ale, a 6% abv ale originally brewed by Anchor Brewing Company as a special in 1975 to commemorate Paul Revere's midnight ride in 1775 which marked the start of the American War of Independence, was seen by Michael Jackson as the first modern American ale.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] The beer was popular, and became a regular in 1983.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] Jack McAuliffe of the New Albion Brewing Company was brewing his New Albion Ale by 1976, inspired by the ales he had tasted in Scotland.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] The beer was (at the time) vigorously hopped with American Cascade hops, refermented in the bottle, and not straw in color – all qualities the popular beer style of the time, i.e. pale lagers, did not possess.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] While the company brewed for fewer than 6 years at only 7.5 barrels (217 US gallons) per week, it inspired many more pioneers and imitators.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] The first brewery to successfully commercialize the use of significant quantities of American hops in the style of APA was the Sierra Nevada Brewing Company, which brewed the first experimental batch of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale in November 1980, distributing the finished version in March 1981.
[src:copper-ale/american-pale-ale] Another pioneer of the hoppy American pale ale was Bert Grant of Yakima Brewing.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] Some varieties of copper ale may be produced to have a bitter flavor, such as that of a bitter.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] Beer brewed with dark malt may contribute to a copper-colored beer.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] Copper ale is the flagship beer of Otter Creek Brewing, a craft brewery located in Middlebury, Vermont.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] It is also produced by other U.S. companies, such as Boulder Beer Company in Boulder, Colorado.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] In Australia, the James Squire brand of copper ale named The Constable Copper Ale was produced.
[src:copper-ale/copper-ale] It is also produced by Alosta Brewing Company in Covina, California, in collaboration with the band +LĪVE+ to celebrate their 8× platinum album *Throwing Copper*.
